reviewText: I was fortunate to see this movie during a private showing.  It is one that will keep your interest from the moment it starts until the very end.  Girl on the Train has many twists and turns and definitely keeps you guessing until the last scene.  It will leave you asking more questions about what just happened!  Worth watching more than once.

Henry Ian Cusick plays Danny who is an Englishman making documentaries in the US. One day he sees a girl on a train who has been crying. He is strangely drawn to her and decides to act on his impulses. She is enigmatic and mysterious and he finds himself wanting to see her again.

Then they do meet and she uses her feminine ways to get him to act out of character and take him down a path that once he has set foot on it, there is no turning back.

Now this is a well written, filmed and acted film. There is a lot of clever observations on life and some real chemistry between the main players. The film works by using flash backs to flesh out what has already transpired and it is done rather well. The problem is that it is all a bit too contrived and unbelievable and the dnouement is just a bit too much to be taken seriously so it loses marks big time.

Poor,poor production, writing,story and sound effects in a cynically packaged product.  The cover has a woman going under a tunnel(as in the film)
and when you buy it in a shop you think you are buying the popular story(from the novel and film). I can't believe I was suckered into this scam-product of immense inferiority. Once you've removed the packaging you can't take it back. The film can be compared to being taken for a ride as
the documentary film maker is by the young woman on the train. The actors speak in shadow a lot or have their backs to you, so don't matter what you do you can't tap into the impoverished meanings on offer. It's basically about a man picking a woman up on a train, but really she's using him
to get him to do something(I won't say what). It's only 1.25 hours long too. Hitching a 'ride' by the director onto a superior product is so intolerable
otherwise theit film would never had been seen or purchased by the unwary consumer. By the way, no subtitles. Disgusting! Immense pile of
mediocrity disguised as an art film.

Lets get serious. This movie may be the most over-hyped this year. It was a low budget affair with a strange story line and a weird ending, or no ending at all. To me it was borderline ignorant. My advice is to only buy when the price falls to ten bucks. Oh, one thing that really got me upset was the shots of the train going down the track while making the click-clack sound of wheels passing over rail joints. My Lord, how stupid. The rail was continuously welded rail or CWR, also called ribbon rail. It had no joints, hence, it can not make the click-clack noise as the train passes by. Overall, dumb movie. Just dump.

I know this was based on a book, which I have not read by the way.  But I can't imagine the book is a lot more interesting than the movie. The movie just feels very contrived.  The dialogue and narration,  which work well in a novel format,  did not translate well at all to the screen. Then the ration is long and tedious, and the dialogue is just too forced.  I saw the plot twist and the ending coming from miles away.  I know it's very hard to translate a book into a screenplay. And unfortunately, the screenplay writer did not do a good job on this one.

This "The Girl on the Train" movie is a psychological intrigue. The movie has very little action. It is all about the dialogue between a movie maker and a girl he spots on the train. He approaches her and begins a conversation. When she gets off the train, all he knows about her is her name. Some time later, she spots him in the train terminal and approaches him. This begins their friendship and a long series of conversations.

The girl learns about his work, a documentary about a Jewish survivor of the Holocaust, and the filming of the Jewish man intertwines with the conversations between the girl and the movie maker, which also intertwines with the movie maker being questioned by the police post-girl. There are glimmers that show the movie maker has been hurt, physically, because of the girl, but we don't know how until the end.

To some, this could be a very boring movie because we are so used to lots of action, but if you can hang with the conversations, the end will blow your mind.

I was surprised when I read the other reviews of this movie and I think those reviewers were annoyed because it wasn't the story they expected. (They expected it to be the Paula Hawkins story by the same name). But really, it's a good movie.  Thoughtful, cerebral, the threads of the story delicately drawn and interwoven. It will keep you thinking about it for a long time.  The movie deals with  how well we can know another human being?  Is what we know of them a story we tell ourselves? And knowing that, is love merely an illusion? It turns these questions around and inside out  as a documentary filmmaker becomes intrigued by a woman he meets on a train.  There is one speech by the woman at the end of the film that is total gobbledegook and should be cut.  But other than that, it's a very well done film. Every time we think it has ended, we get one more glimpse, and another and another that challenges what we know of truth and makes us think.  I suspect the ones who didn't like the film and fell asleep were expecting action adventure.  You have to pay attention and think, but that's what art should call us to do.

I thought this would be a film version of Paula Hawkins's wonderful "The Girl on the Train," but it appears to be something quite different. The narrator is supposed to be Rachel, an alcoholic who rides the same commuter train every day to London and back even though she has lost her job. She spends her time peering into the homes of the people she passes as the train whizzes by--she imagines or in fact sees a man and woman fighting and the woman disappears--the book is about perception. Is she a reliable narrator, or has alcohol so seeped into her being that her view of reality can no longer be trusted? The movie is ridiculous. The narrator is a male; the girl on the train is a perfectly sane (it turns out) murderer--it just doesn't work--even the setting has changed. The plot takes place in New York, not London--it's all topsy turvy. I saw this had a bad review in T New York Times, but I wanted to give it a chance. If you want to watch a C grade mystery viewed from the perspective of a man who can't be sure what he is seeing, then rent it and enjoy it for what it is. It's just NOT Hawkins' novel made into an intriguing film.

Outstanding, How many of us wish we had it to do all over again (what ever "it" is) even if just for a while. So many of us live alternate lives in our mind but never take that step an bring the make believe self to life. I've done it. One time I was at a coctail party at the house of a girl I was dateing. I was dressed all in black. When asked what I did for a living, I thought, what if I were different from all the other guests at the party. Everyone worked in a little cube, for some large corporate organization, dressed pretty much like everyone else, and did the same thing day after day.  Who knows you might do that now. Back to my story, so when asked I told them that I was an  Catholic Priest. I told them that I know longer preformed the duties of a Priest but told them that once a Priest - always a Priest . Just like getting an MBA from some School of Business, you may no longer do what you were trained to do but you'll always be an MBA. Yes, I lied to these people but it was so much fun and interesting. At the end of the evening I told them all the truth and we all had a laugh over it. No one was hurt, but for a couple of hours I was some one else.

Well, I thought this was following the plot of the 2016 movie, but no.  It was odd... and stayed odd.  At first the conversational exchanges were entertaining, but I realized that neither party challenged the other, as if they just accepted what the other said as truth and they did this through the entire movie.  As the movie progressed it became less and less believable, and by the last quarter,  I was exasperated with the mindless babbling as if they were intellectuals, and apparently the writer/director figured the audience was too illiterate (or sleeping) to notice nothing was making much sense any more.  Were we supposed to not notice or be impressed by the ramblings?  Not here.  I went from being entertained and mentally alert trying to figure it all out to "I can't wait until this is over", and then I felt I wasted my time.  Glad it was free with my Prime.

I wanted to like this film more. It has a serene quality despite its urban setting and it does have some good points. But there are definitely more things that make you realize it had a low budget, such as the lead actress not being able to act, along with a few others. I understand what it was trying to achieve, trying to pull us into a mystery by letting us know up front, via the police-interview device, that something bad was going to happen. But you never are quite convinced of any of the character's motivations so a little twist at the end becomes a big "who cares".

It also doesn't help that on the surface, this film tries to be about love or storytelling, but at its heart, it is about lying. No one wants to be the gullible fool, nor will find it easy to relate to a main character whom we see duped not once, not twice, but three times.

This movie has the classic noire elements of The Man Who Gets Involved with The Wrong Kind of Girl only to be Sucked Into an Amoral Reality. In this case, Henry Ian Cusick is a documentary film-maker. For no apparent reason, he becomes smitten with Lexi, a girl he meets on a train. They share clever banter.  She gives him a fake number and gets off at the next stop. Then, although he's been looking for her, she finds him and asks him to follow a man around - who she doesn't say is her husband, but doesn't say is not her husband - for no explicit reason.  Because he's smitten, he does, and from there the bad decisions pile up until there are bodies and the police is looking at him as either the victim or the suspect.

The story is engaging, particularly compared to so much of the dreck that's out there.  The writing gets a bit pretentious and stilted when it waxes lyrical.  Because Cusick is a film-maker, we have metaphors up the whazoo.

Along with another reviewer, I wonder about the Catholic element.  Everyone seems to be Catholic and sporting a connection to St. Jude.  Obviously, someone with more film criticism experience can unpack the metaphors there.

The conclusion does deliver a bit of a minor film noire twist.

If you are a fan of flim noire, this is minor noire, but you will enjoy it.

If you are looking for explosions and gunfights, just walk on by.

This is a movie about the power of fiction to tell the truth, and about the worth of holding out for idealism against cynicism. These themes are bound into an engaging psychological thriller, and the title is a riff on the classic Strangers on a Train (1951). I would compare it in some ways to After Hours (1985), another great American noir movie about a nice guy who gets in over his head, and both The Girl on the Train and After Hours play some with "dream versus reality". I have not seen any reviews that mention how important Catholicism is to the atmosphere of the movie --despite the prominence of saints' medals, little crosses, and one scary nail. It isn't a perfect movie: the dialogue sometimes hits a flat note when it's trying to sing, and some of the "movie about a guy who makes movies" stuff is a little trite. But the visual accomplishment is high, and the characters are people you want to watch for all of the rather brief 80 minutes that they share your imagination. Well worth seeing. (And for those of you in California: don't be scared off by the brain-dead review that ran in the LA Times.)

At first, there's nothing complicated about this movie, until you realize that the girl on the train is one mysterious person! I suppose the moral is, "Be careful who you try and get to know." A real surprise ending and proof that you really can't judge a book by its cover. Henry Ian Cusick and Nicki Aycox are naturals for their roles in this flick!
